00:55:45,224 --> 00:55:45,684
type of thing.

1244
00:55:46,145 --> 00:55:48,106
And this one's remarkable for the amount of custom content

1245
00:55:48,166 --> 00:55:49,107
that they managed to use.

1246
00:55:49,647 --> 00:55:51,068
We don't have snow in the game, by the way.

1247
00:55:51,729 --> 00:55:52,950
They managed to do this.

1248
00:55:54,031 --> 00:55:55,091
They built this giant snow lodge.

1249
00:55:55,171 --> 00:55:56,893
So basically, these teenage friends

1250
00:55:56,953 --> 00:55:58,434
come to this lodge for a weekend.

1251
00:55:59,935 --> 00:56:02,037
This screen, for instance, there's not a single item

1252
00:56:02,077 --> 00:56:03,438
on this screen that we ship with the game.

1253
00:56:03,978 --> 00:56:07,300
They created all the skins, all the objects, the wallpaper,

1254
00:56:07,360 --> 00:56:09,502
the windows, the floor, everything was user created.

1255
00:56:11,201 --> 00:56:12,042
We don't have ski lifts.

1256
00:56:12,582 --> 00:56:16,946
So we don't have skiing.

1257
00:56:17,626 --> 00:56:19,228
Somehow they turned The Sims into a skiing game.

1258
00:56:19,268 --> 00:56:20,689
They made custom meshes.

1259
00:56:21,270 --> 00:56:23,672
They made custom groundscape, custom trees, and all this,

1260
00:56:23,732 --> 00:56:25,213
and made The Sims ski somehow.

1261
00:56:25,233 --> 00:56:26,134
I mean, it just blows my mind.

1262
00:56:27,107 --> 00:56:31,327
So, but basically the story here is that her dead lover appears to her in the night, one

1263
00:56:31,347 --> 00:56:32,588
of the people who showed up at the lodge.

1264
00:56:33,128 --> 00:56:34,028
She meets him in the forest.

1265
00:56:34,228 --> 00:56:36,788
They decide they wanted to get married before, and so they finally get married.

1266
00:56:37,769 --> 00:56:41,469
The next morning, the guy that she came with ends up dead on the lawn.

1267
00:56:42,390 --> 00:56:43,010
They kind of panic.

1268
00:56:43,030 --> 00:56:43,670
They don't know what to do.

1269
00:56:44,230 --> 00:56:45,850
They basically bury him inside a snowman.

1270
00:56:49,871 --> 00:56:52,451
And of course, the next day he wins the snowman contest.

1271
00:56:53,932 --> 00:56:55,632
As the sun comes out, he starts melting, you know.

1272
00:56:57,158 --> 00:57:00,481
So this is a good example of how the fans are feeding on themselves now.

1273
00:57:00,661 --> 00:57:03,043
Basically, the content artists are producing enough content

1274
00:57:03,083 --> 00:57:06,145
where the storytellers can now grab that and do really cool stuff with it.

1275
00:57:06,745 --> 00:57:08,407
These are the credits at the end of this story.

1276
00:57:08,427 --> 00:57:11,349
They're actually writing credits as to what fansites they got what objects from.

1277
00:57:12,330 --> 00:57:14,131
So there's this nice synergy, I think, happening.

1278
00:57:15,553 --> 00:57:16,693
Now, this next one's a little weird.

1279
00:57:18,975 --> 00:57:19,716
Starbucks sucks.

1280
00:57:20,853 --> 00:57:24,095
Now, what's funny is this isn't Starbucks in general sucks.

1281
00:57:24,235 --> 00:57:27,436
It's one particular Starbucks on 47th Avenue in New York sucks.

1282
00:57:29,917 --> 00:57:32,558
And this guy just goes on and on about how he has to wait in line,

1283
00:57:32,598 --> 00:57:35,719
and people answer their old cell phone right at the front of the line,

1284
00:57:35,759 --> 00:57:39,101
and hold up everybody, and weird people hang out there all night,

1285
00:57:40,061 --> 00:57:44,183
and homeless people come in and drink the cream, and all this stuff.

1286
00:57:44,203 --> 00:57:48,124
But then at the very end, he says, oh, by the way,

1287
00:57:48,304 --> 00:57:50,405
there's this little coffee cart down the street that doesn't suck.

1288
00:57:52,571 --> 00:57:54,732
And I'm always wondering who uploaded this story,

1289
00:57:55,412 --> 00:57:57,034
if it was the guy with the coffee cart or not.

1290
00:57:58,795 --> 00:58:01,296
Okay, last thing I want to show you real quickly is technically

1291
00:58:01,336 --> 00:58:04,078
the least impressive, but emotionally,

1292
00:58:04,098 --> 00:58:05,019
I think the most impressive.

1293
00:58:05,499 --> 00:58:08,161
And this was somebody's story about how their sister got

1294
00:58:08,221 --> 00:58:09,942
out of an abusive relationship, a true story.

1295
00:58:11,612 --> 00:58:17,615
I won't read it to you, it's very long, but it basically describes how her sister got into this relationship, the guy who seemed okay at first, he turned into a jerk.

1296
00:58:18,176 --> 00:58:25,219
He started verbally abusing her, eventually got more physical, and then how eventually she, you know, got the gets together to call the police and get him out of her life.

1297
00:58:25,860 --> 00:58:32,703
But you could tell that the game was kind of this catharsis for getting this off her chest and hoping to, you know, spread the word to other people who might be in a similar situation.

1298
00:58:32,723 --> 00:58:37,266
And the fact that a game can be used for something like this is astounding to me. I mean, I really...

1299
00:58:38,192 --> 00:58:42,093
like to think that more into the future, our games can enable this type of communication.

1300
00:58:43,754 --> 00:58:48,977
Now, the last thing I want to talk about here real briefly is interactive storytelling. I've

1301
00:58:48,997 --> 00:58:54,039
always been really happy in my little sandbox doing these open-ended games, these simulations,

1302
00:58:54,099 --> 00:58:58,441
and I've always really avoided the idea of interactive story. But at this point, as you

1303
00:58:58,461 --> 00:59:01,923
can see, our fans are going to basically drag me into it whether I like it or not.

1304
00:59:02,879 --> 00:59:05,281
So I've been thinking about this quite a bit lately,

1305
00:59:06,181 --> 00:59:07,142
how we might enable this.

1306
00:59:07,202 --> 00:59:09,704
What's happening right now is the simulation is going off

1307
00:59:09,724 --> 00:59:11,726
and doing one thing, and the fans are saying,

1308
00:59:12,066 --> 00:59:12,647
oh, to hell with that.

1309
00:59:12,687 --> 00:59:14,448
I'm going to tell my story over this direction.

1310
00:59:15,069 --> 00:59:16,890
And frequently, they're having to take these sims that just

1311
00:59:16,930 --> 00:59:20,413
want to pee and eat and sit in front of the TV,

1312
00:59:20,733 --> 00:59:21,294
and they're grabbing them.

1313
00:59:21,334 --> 00:59:21,894
No, stand over here.

1314
00:59:21,914 --> 00:59:22,675
I need to take this shot.

1315
00:59:23,135 --> 00:59:25,417
And so they're like these little actors on strike

1316
00:59:25,657 --> 00:59:27,359
that you're trying to manipulate to take the screenshots.

1317
00:59:28,139 --> 00:59:30,161
And so what we need to do is try to get these things more

1318
00:59:30,201 --> 00:59:30,741
to convergent.

1319
00:59:31,182 --> 00:59:31,982
Bring them back into line.

1320
00:59:33,141 --> 00:59:35,522
So we've got basically this open-ended space, you know,

1321
00:59:35,582 --> 00:59:39,025
you can go in any direction in, but it's very flat dramatically.

1322
00:59:39,565 --> 00:59:41,266
Now drama, you know, is linear,

1323
00:59:41,607 --> 00:59:44,308
but it has this added dimension that we don't have.

1324
00:59:44,349 --> 00:59:46,610
And so how do we get this added dimension of drama

1325
00:59:47,171 --> 00:59:48,391
in our open-ended space?

1326
00:59:50,493 --> 00:59:53,015
I think really the path to this I see is not teaching the

1327
00:59:53,055 --> 00:59:56,397
computer to tell a story, but rather teaching it

1328
00:59:56,437 --> 00:59:57,378
to recognize a story.

1329
00:59:58,466 --> 01:00:00,467
If when you were playing these stories out in the Sims,

1330
01:00:00,667 --> 01:00:03,148
if the computer could actually get some sense of the story

1331
01:00:03,188 --> 01:00:05,589
that's in your head, it could then start helping you a bit.

1332
01:00:08,290 --> 01:00:10,912
It might at first be just a very simple thematic recognition.

1333
01:00:10,972 --> 01:00:11,872
It might look at the things you've

1334
01:00:11,892 --> 01:00:13,913
bought in the Sims and the interactions you've chosen.

1335
01:00:14,413 --> 01:00:16,654
Oh, you tend to kiss a lot, and you buy this type of stuff.

1336
01:00:16,674 --> 01:00:18,355
I think you're doing sort of a romantic story.

1337
01:00:18,975 --> 01:00:21,456
Or you buy, you know, hearts, heads in jars,

1338
01:00:22,197 --> 01:00:23,677
or shackles in your dungeon.

1339
01:00:23,777 --> 01:00:25,378
And it might say, oh, that looks kind of like horror.

1340
01:00:25,738 --> 01:00:26,559
And it looks at what you're doing.

1341
01:00:27,457 --> 01:00:30,539
It might even drive events to resolve it later.

1342
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:32,901
If it's not quite sure if you're doing a horror or comedy,

1343
01:00:33,281 --> 01:00:35,343
you might walk into a room, and then there's

1344
01:00:35,423 --> 01:00:37,865
a chainsaw and a cream pie, and it's looking

1345
01:00:37,885 --> 01:00:38,705
to see which one you pick up.

1346
01:00:40,006 --> 01:00:40,927
Now, there are a number of approaches

1347
01:00:40,967 --> 01:00:41,907
we can take towards this.

1348
01:00:42,228 --> 01:00:43,408
One might be language parsing.

1349
01:00:44,029 --> 01:00:45,930
In language parsing, this is the way

1350
01:00:45,950 --> 01:00:47,411
computers try to understand natural language.

1351
01:00:47,471 --> 01:00:48,572
They'll look at the string of words,

1352
01:00:49,132 --> 01:00:50,733
and from those, try to build higher and higher levels

1353
01:00:50,794 --> 01:00:53,836
of features, and eventually parse it into a complete sentence.

1354
01:00:54,825 --> 01:00:56,768
I suspect there might be something similar possible

1355
01:00:56,808 --> 01:00:58,970
with story parsing, where you look at an event stream

1356
01:00:59,370 --> 01:01:01,032
and look for higher and higher levels of structure

1357
01:01:01,493 --> 01:01:03,815
coming up to build, the computer can

1358
01:01:03,835 --> 01:01:04,656
build its understanding on.

1359
01:01:06,311 --> 01:01:08,232
Let's assume that, for instance, we could do this.

1360
01:01:08,612 --> 01:01:10,292
If the computer could parse this story,

1361
01:01:10,352 --> 01:01:11,433
then it could actually start changing

1362
01:01:11,473 --> 01:01:13,433
the presentation of the story in something like The Sims.

1363
01:01:14,013 --> 01:01:15,894
We could start having the camera angles change.

1364
01:01:16,014 --> 01:01:17,534
We could have the lighting change, the music.

1365
01:01:17,975 --> 01:01:19,155
So if it thinks you're doing horror,

1366
01:01:19,595 --> 01:01:20,655
the lights start to come down.

1367
01:01:21,035 --> 01:01:22,016
The spooky music starts.

1368
01:01:22,056 --> 01:01:23,436
You see lightning in the background.

1369
01:01:23,996 --> 01:01:26,617
The camera gets really close in, ambient sound effects,

1370
01:01:26,877 --> 01:01:27,437
all this stuff.

1371
01:01:29,743 --> 01:01:31,345
The next step would be probably for the computer

1372
01:01:31,365 --> 01:01:32,646
to actually start driving the events.

1373
01:01:32,706 --> 01:01:34,488
Rather than the events being random,

1374
01:01:35,068 --> 01:01:37,050
they are now events there to support your story.

1375
01:01:39,513 --> 01:01:42,796
Another way to look at this is that we have users always

1376
01:01:42,836 --> 01:01:45,399
in the game trying to find these success landscapes.

1377
01:01:46,480 --> 01:01:49,603
If the computer can detect what goal that a user is trying

1378
01:01:49,623 --> 01:01:50,384
to pursue in the game.

1379
01:01:51,286 --> 01:01:54,527
then perhaps, so say that a million people are playing this game every day

1380
01:01:55,307 --> 01:01:58,229
and after they play it there's some fitness test. It can measure how long you've played,

1381
01:01:58,769 --> 01:02:02,310
maybe you scored at the end, you give it a one to ten, oh I really like that experience today.

1382
01:02:03,150 --> 01:02:05,631
Then it goes back up to the server and it compares all the results.

1383
01:02:05,951 --> 01:02:10,433
So at the top level we can have the server discovering these rules of story.

1384
01:02:10,513 --> 01:02:12,614
It's not like we're trying to engineer story grammar.

1385
01:02:13,314 --> 01:02:15,955
What we're trying to do is develop a system to where we have enough information.

1386
01:02:16,787 --> 01:02:19,790
for the servers at the top end to discover this.

1387
01:02:19,830 --> 01:02:21,192
This is very much like SETI at home.

1388
01:02:21,632 --> 01:02:24,135
We're doing a vast parallel search, except in this case,

1389
01:02:24,455 --> 01:02:26,678
we really are using parallel things like SETI at home.

1390
01:02:27,639 --> 01:02:31,343
So I think long term, this might really be practical.

1391
01:02:31,623 --> 01:02:33,064
And of course, you can look at different players,

1392
01:02:33,085 --> 01:02:34,586
and they're going to want to play the games in different

1393
01:02:34,606 --> 01:02:34,886
ways.

1394
01:02:35,427 --> 01:02:36,909
So a mapping that might work for me

1395
01:02:37,329 --> 01:02:38,510
won't necessarily work for you.

1396
01:02:39,507 --> 01:02:41,288
So at some point you'll want to classify the players.

1397
01:02:41,308 --> 01:02:43,249
It might say, oh, that's the type of player that really

1398
01:02:43,269 --> 01:02:44,370
enjoys the comedy experience.

1399
01:02:45,411 --> 01:02:46,671
So they get this mapping, and they'll

1400
01:02:46,691 --> 01:02:48,692
be evolving a certain mapping for that group of players.

1401
01:02:49,033 --> 01:02:51,234
These other players we know like to kill and torture

1402
01:02:51,274 --> 01:02:52,815
their sims, and so we're going to give them

1403
01:02:52,855 --> 01:02:53,995
a completely different experience.

1404
01:02:55,056 --> 01:02:57,517
So that's about it on this.

1405
01:02:59,569 --> 01:03:00,190
Oh, one more thing.

1406
01:03:00,210 --> 01:03:03,275
Once you've done this, assuming we could do this,

1407
01:03:03,455 --> 01:03:05,799
which is a big if, I know it's a very difficult target.

1408
01:03:06,540 --> 01:03:08,303
Once you've finished this, once you've

1409
01:03:08,323 --> 01:03:10,406
done the parsing, presentation, computers

1410
01:03:10,427 --> 01:03:12,270
helping you tell the story, in essence,

1411
01:03:12,290 --> 01:03:13,171
you've made a movie at the end.

1412
01:03:13,822 --> 01:03:15,002
which you can then share with your friends.

1413
01:03:15,082 --> 01:03:16,863
Maybe you can even go back and edit the camera angles.

1414
01:03:17,743 --> 01:03:18,943
Other people at the game, you should

1415
01:03:18,963 --> 01:03:20,824
be able to send this movie, very much like Quake movies

1416
01:03:21,764 --> 01:03:23,325
were doing, which was a very cool idea.

1417
01:03:23,805 --> 01:03:25,785
If you have the engine, it's a very small amount of data

1418
01:03:25,805 --> 01:03:26,926
I have to send you to send the movie.

1419
01:03:27,266 --> 01:03:30,327
Or it could be saved out as a JPEG or an MPEG

1420
01:03:30,787 --> 01:03:32,447
and given around to other people, posted on websites.

1421
01:03:34,208 --> 01:03:36,489
So really, what I think this is going to end up being more like

1422
01:03:36,549 --> 01:03:37,229
is the Truman Show.

1423
01:03:38,068 --> 01:03:40,589
where you're Truman, kind of living your life out.

1424
01:03:40,869 --> 01:03:42,269
There's boundaries, but the boundaries

1425
01:03:42,329 --> 01:03:43,630
are as far away as we can make them.

1426
01:03:44,310 --> 01:03:45,711
And the computer is back there, sitting there,

1427
01:03:45,731 --> 01:03:46,651
looking at what you're doing, saying,

1428
01:03:47,311 --> 01:03:48,231
that might be dramatic.

1429
01:03:48,472 --> 01:03:49,332
What if I had this happen?

1430
01:03:49,432 --> 01:03:50,812
It may be trying things on you all the time.

1431
01:03:50,912 --> 01:03:54,234
The computer might be sending NPCs into your life,

1432
01:03:54,294 --> 01:03:55,934
seeing, oh, I see this love story developing.

1433
01:03:55,974 --> 01:03:58,275
I better make the jealous ex-girlfriend appear

1434
01:03:58,295 --> 01:03:58,895
at the door right now.

1435
01:03:59,876 --> 01:04:02,216
So always trying to keep the dramatic tension going.

1436
01:04:04,437 --> 01:04:05,858
So that's about all I have to say on that.

1437
01:04:05,978 --> 01:04:07,638
I just wanted to close with one more remark.

1438
01:04:08,193 --> 01:04:11,233
And that's that in game design over the years,

1439
01:04:11,533 --> 01:04:13,854
I found that two things really have made the biggest

1440
01:04:13,914 --> 01:04:17,295
difference that I've seen in design.

1441
01:04:17,315 --> 01:04:18,755
And that has to do with self-confidence

1442
01:04:19,495 --> 01:04:20,395
and determination.

1443
01:04:22,255 --> 01:04:24,376
A lot of times, you'll come up with a really crazy idea.

1444
01:04:25,376 --> 01:04:26,916
And you'll start telling people about it.

1445
01:04:26,936 --> 01:04:27,757
And they'll say, that sucks.

1446
01:04:27,777 --> 01:04:28,417
That's horrible.

1447
01:04:28,597 --> 01:04:31,177
And frequently, that's not always the case.

1448
01:04:33,138 --> 01:04:34,278
I've only had two games.

1449
01:04:34,708 --> 01:04:39,110
where I had that experience where most of the people I told my idea for the game, they said,

1450
01:04:39,430 --> 01:04:42,510
that's a horrible idea. And those two games were SimCity and The Sims.

1451
01:04:44,251 --> 01:04:47,392
All the other games I would describe to people and say, oh, sounds great, let's do it. And they

1452
01:04:47,432 --> 01:04:54,294
were all on board. They understood it. So basically, if you have an idea like that,

1453
01:04:54,734 --> 01:04:59,615
and you go around telling everybody and they tell you it sucks, well, pragmatically, it probably

1454
01:04:59,635 --> 01:05:00,835
does suck. But...

1455
01:05:02,345 --> 01:05:03,586
there's really a chance that it doesn't,

1456
01:05:03,606 --> 01:05:05,007
that you're actually going to jump outside the box.

1457
01:05:05,047 --> 01:05:06,208
If other people don't understand it,

1458
01:05:06,709 --> 01:05:07,990
that's probably a good thing.

1459
01:05:08,610 --> 01:05:10,192
And that's where the determination comes in.

1460
01:05:10,572 --> 01:05:12,094
At that point, it's entirely up to you

1461
01:05:12,114 --> 01:05:14,636
to have the determination to fight, kick, and scream,

1462
01:05:14,656 --> 01:05:16,297
do whatever it takes to get that idea out there.

1463
01:05:17,158 --> 01:05:20,861
And maybe, you know, maybe it'll be a success.

1464
01:05:21,582 --> 01:05:22,163
So thank you.

